Building a histogram

Imagine a histogram for the results from a very easy quiz with 1010 questions.

  1. Answer the following questions about the histogram:

    1. What quantity should go on the xx-axis of the histogram?
    2. What quantity should go on the yy-axis of the histogram?
    Answer:
    1. The quantity on the xx-axis should be: .
    2. The quantity on the yy-axis should be: .
    HINT: <no title>
    [−0 points ⇒ 2 / 2 points left]

    Reread the question. The yy-axis on a histogram always shows the number of data values (the frequency of values). The xx-axis always shows the values for the data themselves.

    STEP: Select the correct axis labels
    [−2 points ⇒ 0 / 2 points left]

    This question is about making a histogram. Specifically, we need to figure out what quantities should go on the axes for a histogram about the situation in the question.

    The horizontal axis in a histogram must always show the possible values of the data. In this case the data values are the quiz results. So the xx-axis must show the marks.

    For any histogram the yy-axis always shows the number of data values in the various intervals. (This is often called the frequency.)

    For the histogram described in this question:

    1. The variable on the xx-axis should be: Marks.
    2. The variable on the yy-axis should be: Number of results.

  2. Which of the pictures below shows the shape we should expect for the histogram? (Reminder: the data are about the results from a very easy quiz with 1010 questions.)

    A

    B

    C

    D
    Answer:

    The most reasonable shape to expect is choice .

    HINT: <no title>
    [−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

    Do you expect most of the quiz results to be in the middle of the values, or will they mostly be smaller values? Or will they be spread out equally for all the values?

    STEP: Think about the way the data values will be spread out
    [−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

    To answer this question, we need to think about how the data values for the quiz results will be spread out.

    The four images below show these basic situations:

    A

    Balanced shape: Most data values are in the centre with a balanced number of values on each side. This means values in the middle are more common than values on the left side or the right side. So a balanced distribution is more or less symmetric with the peak in the middle.

    B

    Flat shape: All data values are spread out equally. So values on the left side are just as common as values on the right side and in the middle. This typically represents something random. Note that a flat shape is not exactly flat - but it has no significant peaks.

    C

    Skewed right shape: The data values are clumped up on the left side with a "tail" to the right. This shows that for some reason the data values on the right side are less common. This would happen if larger values (on the right side) are harder to achieve than smaller values (on the left side).

    D

    Skewed left shape: The data values are clumped up on the right side with a "tail" to the left. This shows that for some reason the data values on the left side are less common. This would happen if larger values (on the right side) are easier to achieve than smaller values (on the left side).

    So which of these is the most reasonable to expect? The question states that the quiz was very easy. That means most students probably got pretty high marks, and not many students would get low marks. So the most likely shape for the real histogram is the skewed left shape.

    NOTE: It is possible that the histogram will have a different shape - we can't know for sure if we do not have the data values. So our answer is based on reasonable expectations about quiz results.

    Therefore the most reasonable shape to expect is choice D.

Common histogram errors

The histogram below shows a data set about how many minutes 5454 different people spent crying after watching Titanic. But there is a problem: there is an error in the histogram.

What is the problem with this histogram? Select your answer from the choices below.

A The intervals should have equal widths
B The axis labels are swapped
C The y-axis values are incorrect
D There are not enough intervals
Answer:

The problem is choice .

HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

Compare the histogram to what you expect to see. What is different? What does not agree with the information given in the question?

STEP: Compare the given histogram to what you expect to see
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

We need to identify the problem with the histogram given above. To do this we need to compare the histogram to what we expect to see.

The problem here is that the third interval is not the same width as the other intervals. All intervals on a histogram should be the same width so that we can make useful comparisons between the number of data values in each interval. If one interval is wider than another, we cannot interpret the height of that bar effectively.

The problem with the histogram is that the intervals should have equal widths, which is choice A.

Histograms vs bar graphs

  1. What is the difference between a histogram and a bar graph? Or are they the same?

    Pick your answer from the choices below.

    A Histograms show categorical data while bar graphs show continuous quantitative data.
    B Histograms show continuous quantitative data while bar graphs show categorical data.
    C Histograms show qualitative data while bar graphs do not.
    D There is no difference between a histogram and a bar graph.
    Answer:

    The correct description of the difference is option .

    HINT: <no title>
    [−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

    Histograms are used for data which is grouped into intervals. Bar graphs show data which is organised into categories.

    STEP: Determine what types of data are appropriate for histograms and bar graphs
    [−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

    Histograms and bar graphs are easy to confuse because they look like each other. But they are not the same! The difference is the type of data that they show.

    • Histogram A histogram uses bars to show continuous data. The data must be grouped into intervals. The bars touch each other because the data are continuous. A histogram shows the same information as a frequency polygon, but with bars instead of a line.
    • Bar graph A bar graph uses bars to show categorical data. That means data which are organised into categories. For example, types of cars or different provinces are categories. Such data cannot be grouped in intervals because the categories are separate from each other. The bars often do not touch each other because the data are not continuous.

    One key difference between histograms and bar graphs is the order of the values on the horizontal axis. The values for a histogram must be in order, because the data are continuous. But for bar graphs the order of the values can change. They can change because the categories themselves do not have a specific order.

    TIP: To decide if data belong in a histogram or a bar graph, ask yourself if the order of the data groups can be shifted or not. If the order cannot be shifted, you are dealing with a histogram situation.

    The difference between histograms and bar graphs is that histograms show continuous quantitative data while bar graphs show categorical data. The correct choice is B.

    Submit your answer as:

Suppose we have a data set for the income of a number of people in many different jobs. Which of the pictures below shows the shape we should expect for the histogram?

A

B

C

D
Answer:

The most reasonable shape to expect is choice .

HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

Do you expect most of the data values to be in the middle of the values, or will they mostly be smaller values? Or will they be spread out equally for all the values?

STEP: Think about the way the data values will be spread out
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

To answer this question, we need to think about how the data values for the income of different people will be spread out.

The images in the question show these four basic situations:

A

Balanced shape: Most data values are in the centre with a balanced number of values on each side. This means values in the middle are more common than values on the left side or the right side. So a balanced distribution is more or less symmetric with the peak in the middle.

B

Flat shape: All data values are spread out equally. So values on the left side are just as common as values on the right side and in the middle. This typically represents something random. Note that a flat shape is not exactly flat - but it has no significant peaks.

C

Skewed right shape: The data values are clumped up on the left side with a "tail" to the right. This shows that for some reason the data values on the right side are less common. This would happen if larger values (on the right side) are harder to achieve than smaller values (on the left side).

D

Skewed left shape: The data values are clumped up on the right side with a "tail" to the left. This shows that for some reason the data values on the left side are less common. This would happen if larger values (on the right side) are easier to achieve than smaller values (on the left side).

So which of these is the most reasonable to expect for the income of different people?

For income, there will be a large spread of relatively small values. But there will be a few very large incomes. In fact, the larger the income gets the less common it will be. So the histogram for these data is probably going to be skewed right.

NOTE: It is possible that the histogram will have a different shape - we can't know for sure if we do not have the data values. So our answer is based on reasonable expectations about the situation described in the question.

The most reasonable shape to expect is choice C.

Histograms vs bar graphs

  1. What is the difference between a histogram and a bar graph? Or are they the same?

    Pick your answer from the choices below.

    A Histograms show qualitative data while bar graphs do not.
    B Histograms show data with lines while bar graphs show data with bars.
    C Histograms show continuous quantitative data while bar graphs show categorical data.
    D There is no difference between a histogram and a bar graph.
    Answer:

    The correct description of the difference is option .

    HINT: <no title>
    [−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

    Histograms are used for data which is grouped into intervals. Bar graphs show data which is organised into categories.

    STEP: Determine what types of data are appropriate for histograms and bar graphs
    [−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

    Histograms and bar graphs are easy to confuse because they look like each other. But they are not the same! The difference is the type of data that they show.

    • Histogram A histogram uses bars to show continuous data. The data must be grouped into intervals. The bars touch each other because the data are continuous. A histogram shows the same information as a frequency polygon, but with bars instead of a line.
    • Bar graph A bar graph uses bars to show categorical data. That means data which are organised into categories. For example, types of cars or different provinces are categories. Such data cannot be grouped in intervals because the categories are separate from each other. The bars often do not touch each other because the data are not continuous.

    One key difference between histograms and bar graphs is the order of the values on the horizontal axis. The values for a histogram must be in order, because the data are continuous. But for bar graphs the order of the values can change. They can change because the categories themselves do not have a specific order.

    TIP: To decide if data belong in a histogram or a bar graph, ask yourself if the order of the data groups can be shifted or not. If the order cannot be shifted, you are dealing with a histogram situation.

    The difference between histograms and bar graphs is that histograms show continuous quantitative data while bar graphs show categorical data. The correct choice is C.

    A The graphs do not follow the same scale.
    B The histogram shows frequencies but the ogive shows cumulative frequency.
    C The graphs are not using the same intervals.
    D The ogive is based on the midpoints of the intervals.
    Answer: The correct explanation is .
    HINT: <no title>
    [−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

    How are the histogram and the ogive related to each other?

    STEP: Identify how histograms and ogives are related
    [−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

    This question is about how histograms and ogives are related to each other.

    • Histograms show the frequency for each interval (how many data values are in each interval). Each interval is separate from the others.
    • Ogives show the cumulative frequency for each interval. That means we add the frequencies of the intervals together as we go along.

    So the histogram shows the number of data values in each interval, and each interval is separate. But the ogive keeps adding those values up in a running total. As a result, the ogive keeps rising.

    NOTE: This is also why the ogive rises more quickly than the histogram on the left side of the histogram's peak.

    The correct statement is that the histogram shows frequencies but the ogive shows cumulative frequency, which is choice B.

  1. Which point on the ogive corresponds to the minimum value?

Answer:
  1. The minimum value is at .
  2. The minimum value is .
numeric

[−0 points ⇒ 2 / 2 points left]

The minimum value is at the beginning of the data set. Start by finding this position on the yy-axis.

STEP: Locate the minimum value from its position on the yy-axis
[−1 point ⇒ 1 / 2 points left]

We need to determine which point on the ogive corresponds to the minimum value of the data. This is one of the values in the five number summary which break the data into quartiles:

  • minimum value (0th0th percentile)
  • first quartile (25th25th percentile)
  • median (50th50th percentile)
  • third quartile (75th75th percentile)
  • maximum (100th100th percentile)

We find all these values on the yy-axis. That is because the yy-axis shows the cumulative frequency. And as we move up the yy-axis we are accumulating the data values. They always start at zero and go up to the total number of values in the data set. The graph below shows all five of these values on the ogive. Notice that they split the ogive into four equally tall bands.

NOTE: The question states that there are 4444 data values in the set. So there are 1111 of those values in each quartile.

The minimum value is the value at the beginning of the data. Point BB corresponds to this position on the yy-axis so that is the correct point.

STEP: Read the value of the minimum value from the xx-axis
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 2 points left]

We can find the value of the minimum value from the ogive. But it is easier to use the box-and-whisker plot because it shows the five number summary directly. In contrast, on the ogive we must locate those values on the xx-axis. This is shown below.

The figure above shows how the quartiles connect to the data values. They go through the ogive to the xx-axis. Notice that these locations on the xx-axis are at the same positions as the boundaries on the box-and-whisker plot.

We know that the minimum value corresponds to Point BB, so we can read the value from the xx-axis: it is 22.

NOTE:

Here are two important points about ogives and the five number summary:

  • The vertical lines we added on the ogive come from the quartile boundaries. That is how the quartiles on the yy-axis of the ogive end up making the four sections of a box-and-whisker plot.
  • The box-and-whisker plot is an estimation of the exact plot. This is because the ogive shows grouped data and we do not know the exact values of the data. For example, we do not know that the minimum data value is 22. We only know that the first interval starts at 22. Similarly, we do not know that the median is ≈12≈12: that is an assumption based on the ogive.
  1. The correct point for the minimum value is BB.

Comparing histograms and their ogives

The figure below shows a histogram and an ogive. These two graphs represent the same data set.

  1. The histogram has a peak in the third interval and the bars after that peak get smaller. But the ogive continues to go up. Why does this happen?

    A The histogram shows frequencies but the ogive shows cumulative frequency.
    B The graphs are not using the same intervals.
    C The graphs do not follow the same scale.
    D The ogive is based on the midpoints of the intervals.
    Answer: The correct explanation is .
    HINT: <no title>
    [−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

    How are the histogram and the ogive related to each other?

    STEP: Identify how histograms and ogives are related
    [−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

    This question is about how histograms and ogives are related to each other.

    • Histograms show the frequency for each interval (how many data values are in each interval). Each interval is separate from the others.
    • Ogives show the cumulative frequency for each interval. That means we add the frequencies of the intervals together as we go along.

    So the histogram shows the number of data values in each interval, and each interval is separate. But the ogive keeps adding those values up in a running total. As a result, the ogive keeps rising.

    NOTE: This is also why the ogive rises more quickly than the histogram on the left side of the histogram's peak.

    The correct statement is that the histogram shows frequencies but the ogive shows cumulative frequency, which is choice A.

    [−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

    The picture above shows that the number of data values added to the ogive in every interval is equal to the height of the bar in the histogram. How cool is that?

    1. How many students fell over before 8 minutes?
    2. How many students kept standing on one leg for at least 8 minutes?
    numeric
    numeric
    HINT: <no title>
    [−0 points ⇒ 3 / 3 points left]

    Start by locating the point on the graph which corresponds to 8 minutes. The y-value at that point is the total number of students who have already fallen over by that time.

    STEP: Read the number of students who have fallen over from the graph
    [−1 point ⇒ 2 / 3 points left]

    This question is about finding information on ogives. In this case, both questions focus on a particular point in time: 8 minutes. This corresponds to the point circled below:

    For the first question we need to determine the number of students who fell over before 8 minutes. In other words, what is the total number of students who fell over from the moment everyone started standing on one leg until 8 minutes had passed.

    The point circled above has a time value of 8 minutes (on the x-axis). The y-axis shows cumulative frequency, so we can find the total number of students who fell over by that time on the y-axis.

    So 4 students fell over before 8 minutes.

    STEP: Determine how many students were still standing by 8 minutes
    [−2 points ⇒ 0 / 3 points left]

    The second question asks us to determine how many students kept standing on one leg for at least 8 minutes. This must be all the students who were not in the answer above. So if we figure out how many students there are in total, we can subtract the ones who already fell over to get this answer.

    We can find the total number of students from the final point on the ogive. From one point to the next we keep on adding more students until, at the end, we have added all the students.

    The final point shows that there are 30 students in total. This must be the case because the y-axis shows cumulative frequency. It shows us a running total of the number of students who have fallen over as time passes. This also agrees with the total number of students mentioned in the question!

    From the answer above we know that 4 students fell over before 8 minutes. If there are 30 students in total, the number who kept standing on one leg for at least 8 minutes must be everyone else.

    30−4=26

    There were 26 students who kept standing on one leg for at least 8 minutes.

Cumulative frequency values

Here is a random data set of 17 values:

901110565751155110407

We can group these data into six intervals as shown in the table below. The table shows the frequencies for the data. The table also has a column for cumulative frequency, but it has two numbers missing. Fill in the missing numbers.

Answer:
Interval Frequency Cumulative frequency
0≤x<2 3 3
2≤x<4 0
4≤x<6 6 9
6≤x<8 3
8≤x<10 1 13
10≤x<12 4 17
numeric
numeric
HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 2 / 2 points left]

The cumulative frequency values show the running total for the frequencies.

STEP: Use the frequency values to find the missing values
[−2 points ⇒ 0 / 2 points left]

The frequencies show how many data values are in each interval. But the cumulative frequency adds up the data values from the beginning to the end. In other words, the cumulative frequency is the running total of data values from the first interval to the last interval.

The cumulative frequency at a certain interval is the sum of the frequencies up to and including that interval. For example, to find the second cumulative frequency value we add up the first two frequencies:

3+0=3
NOTE: The second frequency is zero. And that is why the first and the second cumulative frequency values are equal.

Here is the correct table with the answers included:

Interval Frequency Cumulative frequency
0≤x<2 3 3
2≤x<4 0 3
4≤x<6 6 9
6≤x<8 3 12
8≤x<10 1 13
10≤x<12 4 17

The cumulative frequency values show the running total for the frequencies.

STEP: Use the frequency values to find the missing values
[−2 points ⇒ 0 / 2 points left]

The frequencies show how many data values are in each interval. But the cumulative frequency adds up the data values from the beginning to the end. In other words, the cumulative frequency is the running total of data values from the first interval to the last interval.

The cumulative frequency at a certain interval is the sum of the frequencies up to and including that interval. For example, to find the second cumulative frequency value we add up the first two frequencies:

4+0=4
NOTE: The second frequency is zero. And that is why the first and the second cumulative frequency values are equal.

Matching histograms and ogives

The histogram below shows the amount of time it takes for 26 different taxis to reach the centre of Cape Town from a particular suburb.

The data above can also be represented by an ogive. One of the ogives below is the correct ogive for the data. Which ogive is correct?

Answer: The correct ogive is .
HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

Use the shape of the histogram to determine the answer. Remember that tall bars lead to big jumps on an ogive. Similarly, if the histogram does not have any tall peaks then the ogive should have no big jumps.

STEP: Use the shape of the histogram
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

In this question we must figure out how the shape of the histogram translates onto an ogive. Here are some key facts linking histograms and ogives:

  • Tall bars on the histogram correspond to steep sections on an ogive. This is because the tall bars indicate intervals which have a lot of data values.
  • Short bars on the histogram correspond to gentle gradients on an ogive. This is because the short bars indicate intervals which contain few data values.
  • Any interval on the histogram with no bar corresponds to a flat section on an ogive. This is because such an interval contains no data values, so the ogive cannot increase.

The figure below shows how the height of the bars creates the correct ogive.

The histogram in this question has a peak on the right side, in the eighth interval. At the same time, most of the bars on the left side are relatively small. So the corresponding ogive should increase quickly on the right side with the biggest jump in the eighth interval. On the left side it should increase very slowly because the histogram bars there are short.

The correct ogive must be graph D.

  • minimum value (0th percentile)
  • first quartile (25th percentile)
  • median (50th percentile)
  • third quartile (75th percentile)
  • maximum (100th percentile)

  • The vertical lines we added on the ogive come from the quartile boundaries. That is how the quartiles on the y-axis of the ogive end up making the four sections of a box-and-whisker plot.
  • The box-and-whisker plot is an estimation of the exact plot. This is because the ogive shows grouped data and we do not know the exact values of the data. For example, we do not know that the minimum data value is 0. We only know that the first interval starts at 0. The following graph is an ogive (a cumulative frequency curve). It shows data organised into 7 intervals. The total number of data values is 32. Five points on the ogive are labelled A to E. The figure also shows a box-and-whisker plot for the same data.

  1. Which point on the ogive corresponds to the minimum value?
  2. Determine the minimum value.
Answer:
  1. The minimum value is at .
  2. The minimum value is .
numeric
HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 2 / 2 points left]

The minimum value is at the beginning of the data set. Start by finding this position on the y-axis.

STEP: Locate the minimum value from its position on the y-axis
[−1 point ⇒ 1 / 2 points left]

We need to determine which point on the ogive corresponds to the minimum value of the data. This is one of the values in the five number summary which break the data into quartiles:

  • minimum value (0th percentile)
  • first quartile (25th percentile)
  • median (50th percentile)
  • third quartile (75th percentile)
  • maximum (100th percentile)

We find all these values on the y-axis. That is because the y-axis shows the cumulative frequency. And as we move up the y-axis we are accumulating the data values. They always start at zero and go up to the total number of values in the data set. The graph below shows all five of these values on the ogive. Notice that they split the ogive into four equally tall bands.

NOTE: The question states that there are 32 data values in the set. So there are 8 of those values in each quartile.

The minimum value is the value at the beginning of the data. Point A corresponds to this position on the y-axis so that is the correct point.

STEP: Read the value of the minimum value from the x-axis
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 2 points left]

We can find the value of the minimum value from the ogive. But it is easier to use the box-and-whisker plot because it shows the five number summary directly. In contrast, on the ogive we must locate those values on the x-axis. This is shown below.

The figure above shows how the quartiles connect to the data values. They go through the ogive to the x-axis. Notice that these locations on the x-axis are at the same positions as the boundaries on the box-and-whisker plot.

We know that the minimum value corresponds to Point A, so we can read the value from the x-axis: it is 4.

NOTE:

Here are two important points about ogives and the five number summary:

  • The vertical lines we added on the ogive come from the quartile boundaries. That is how the quartiles on the y-axis of the ogive end up making the four sections of a box-and-whisker plot.
  • The box-and-whisker plot is an estimation of the exact plot. This is because the ogive shows grouped data and we do not know the exact values of the data. For example, we do not know that the minimum data value is 4. We only know that the first interval starts at 4. Similarly, we do not know that the median is ≈19: that is an assumption based on the ogive.
  1. The correct point for the minimum value is A.
  2. The value of the minimum value is 4.

Working with ogives: counting values

A group of 22 students counts the number of marbles they each have. This is an ogive describing the data they collected:

How many students had a number of marbles in the following range: 6≤number of marbles<12.

Answer:

Number of students =

numeric
HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 2 / 2 points left]

Start by finding the numbers 6 and 12 on the x-axis. Then you need to read the corresponding cumulative frequency values from the y-axis and use them to get the answer.

STEP: Locate the relevant points on the ogive
[−1 point ⇒ 1 / 2 points left]

Start by finding the numbers 6 and 12 on the x-axis. We need to track those values through the ogive to the corresponding cumulative frequencies. The arrows below show these connections.

The circled points are where the ogive connects the number of marbles to the number of students:

  • The first point says that there are 4 students who have fewer than 6 marbles.
  • The second point says that there are 12 students who have fewer than 12 marbles.
STEP: Subtract to find the answer
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 2 points left]

The number of students with a number of marbles in the required range is the difference between the cumulative frequencies we found above. We need to subtract because the second point, which indicates 12 students, includes the 4 students counted at the first point.

number of students=12−4=8

Therefore, the number of students with marbles in the range 6≤number of marbles<12 is 8.

Interval Frequency Cumulative frequency
0≤x<4 5 5
4≤x<8 2 7
8≤x<12 4 11
12≤x<16 2 13
16≤x<20 1 14

The data in the table make the ogive (cumulative frequency curve) below. There are four points on the graph, labelled A, B, C, and D. Which of the points on the ogive corresponds to the fifth row in the table above?

Answer: The fifth row corresponds to Point .
HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

An ogive is based on cumulative frequency values. So the point which corresponds to the fifth row in the table must include a coordinate equal to 14. Should that be the x-coordinate or the y-coordinate?

STEP: Use the interval and the cumulative frequency for the fifth row
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

An ogive is a line graph which shows the cumulative frequencies for a data set. Cumulative frequencies are a running total of values. In this question, the table shows us the cumulative frequencies (and the frequencies) for a data set which is split into five intervals.

Each row in the table corresponds to one point on the ogive. For each of those points:

  • the x-coordinate is the upper limit of the interval
  • the y-coordinate is the cumulative frequency for that interval

In this case we are interested in the fifth row, which is:

Interval Frequency Cumulative frequency
16≤x<20 1 14

So the point we are looking for is at x=20 and y=14. Which point has the coordinates (20;14)?

NOTE: The meaning of Point D is that from x=0 up to x=20 there are a total of 14 data values in the data set. Those values are not all in the fifth interval - they are spread out amongst the first 5 intervals.

Row 5 tells us that there must be a point at the coordinates (20;14), which is Point D.

Frequency tables and ogives

The table below shows the mass (in grams) that each of the 51 participants in a weight-loss programme lost in total.

Mass loss over four weeks (in grams) Frequency
1 000 ≤m< 1 500 8
1 500 ≤m< 2 000 5
2 000 ≤m< 2 500 4
2 500 ≤m< 3 000 1
3 000 ≤m< 3 500 6
3 500 ≤m< 4 000 9
4 000 ≤m< 4 500 9
4 500 ≤m< 5 000 9

  1. Estimate the average Mass loss, in grams, by the participants over the first four weeks.

    INSTRUCTION: Round your answer to two decimal places.
    Answer:

    The average mass lost is approximately grams.

    numeric
    HINT: <no title>
    [−0 points ⇒ 2 / 2 points left]

    The data in the question are grouped into eight intervals. To estimate the average for grouped data, start by finding the midpoints of the intervals.

    STEP: Find the midpoints of the intervals
    [−1 point ⇒ 1 / 2 points left]

    To estimate the mean (average) value of grouped data, we use the midpoints of the intervals. We do this because we do not know the individual data values - we only know how many data values are in each interval. We use the midpoints because they are the most reasonable assumption for the values of those data values. The midpoint values are:

    1 000≤m<1 500→1 2501 500≤m<2 000→1 7502 000≤m<2 500→2 2502 500≤m<3 000→2 7503 000≤m<3 500→3 2503 500≤m<4 000→3 7504 000≤m<4 500→4 2504 500≤m<5 000→4 750
    STEP: Compute the estimated mean of the data
    [−1 point ⇒ 0 / 2 points left]

    Now we multiply each midpoint by the frequency in the corresponding interval and add it all up. We also need to divide by the total number of participants in the weight-loss programme. The question states that this is 51. So we get:

    Estimatedmean=(1 250⋅8+1 750⋅5+2 250⋅4+2 750⋅1+3 250⋅6+3 750⋅9+4 250⋅9+4 750⋅9)51=164 75051=3 230,39215...≈3 230,39

    The estimated average is 3 230,39 grams.

    [−1 point ⇒ 1 / 2 points left]

    1 000 ≤m< 1 500 8 8
    1 500 ≤m< 2 000 5 13
    2 000 ≤m< 2 500 4 17
    2 500 ≤m< 3 000 1 18
    3 000 ≤m< 3 500 6 24
    3 500 ≤m< 4 000 9 33
    4 000 ≤m< 4 500 9 42
    4 500 ≤m< 5 000 9 51

    [−1 point ⇒ 0 / 2 points left]
